Imagine multiplying two 1000x1000 matrices (C = A times B). The naive algorithm:

for i from 0 to 999:
  for j from 0 to 999:
    for k from 0 to 999:
      C[i,j] = C[i,j] plus A[i,k] times B[k,j]

This accesses B column-by-column (bad cache locality), causing approximately 1000 cache misses per column, totaling approximately 1 million misses. With each miss costing approximately 200 cycles, performance suffers dramatically.

With cache blocking (process 64x64 tiles at a time):

for tile_i from 0 to 15:
  for tile_j from 0 to 15:
    for tile_k from 0 to 15:
      for i from 0 to 63:
        for j from 0 to 63:
          for k from 0 to 63:
            C[i,j] = C[i,j] plus A[i,k] times B[k,j]

Now, a 64x64 tile of A (approximately 16 kilobytes) and B (approximately 16 kilobytes) fit in L2 cache. After the first approximately 32 misses loading the tile, the next approximately 4000 accesses hit cache. Total cache misses drop from 1 million to approximately 10,000. Performance improves by approximately 100x for this memory-bound computation.

This is why high-performance libraries like BLAS spend significant engineering effort on these optimizations—they're not micro-optimizations but essential transformations that directly impact real-world performance.
